WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.085 --> 00:00:04.129
[♪♪♪]

2
00:00:38.205 --> 00:00:42.084
<i>[WOMAN SCREAMING]</i>

3
00:00:56.849 --> 00:00:58.892
WOMAN 2:
<i>Emily!</i>

4
00:00:58.893 --> 00:01:01.479
<i>[WOMAN HOWLS]</i>

5
00:01:21.332 --> 00:01:24.168
[WIND WHISTLING]

6
00:01:48.233 --> 00:01:50.194
{\an8}[KNOCKING]

7
00:02:18.056 --> 00:02:19.431
[METAL CREAKING]

8
00:02:22.351 --> 00:02:23.602
[CATS MEWLING]

9
00:02:35.656 --> 00:02:37.783
[INSECTS BUZZING]

10
00:03:00.848 --> 00:03:03.308
WOMAN:
You're the medical examiner?

11
00:03:10.775 --> 00:03:13.111
[WOMAN SNIFFLING]

12
00:03:14.070 --> 00:03:16.488
{\an8}[WHIMPERS]

13
00:03:27.291 --> 00:03:29.043
Mr. Rose.

14
00:04:00.282 --> 00:04:02.618
[POLICE RADIO CHATTER]

15
00:04:10.668 --> 00:04:12.211
[TICKING]

16
00:04:26.851 --> 00:04:28.393
I'm sorry,
Mr. Rose.

17
00:04:30.270 --> 00:04:33.190
But I cannot state conclusively

18
00:04:33.191 --> 00:04:35.025
that the cause of...

19
00:04:35.026 --> 00:04:38.070
death was natural.

20
00:04:39.279 --> 00:04:41.866
Your daughter, she...

21
00:04:45.327 --> 00:04:48.288
[WIND WHISTLING]

22
00:04:50.290 --> 00:04:51.875
[CREAKING]
<i>[SCREAMS ECHO]</i>

23
00:04:51.876 --> 00:04:55.753
[♪♪♪]

24
00:04:55.754 --> 00:04:58.506
MAN:
Excuse me, Father?

25
00:04:58.507 --> 00:05:01.218
Father Moore.

26
00:05:01.219 --> 00:05:03.345
You'll have to come with me.

27
00:05:12.563 --> 00:05:13.897
<i>Will you plead guilty?</i>

28
00:05:13.898 --> 00:05:15.565
{\an8}<i>Will you comment
on the cause of death?</i>

29
00:05:15.566 --> 00:05:17.525
{\an8}<i>Father, tell us about
the exorcism! Over here!</i>

30
00:05:17.526 --> 00:05:19.819
{\an8}<i>I'm here at Crescent County
Courthouse this afternoon</i>

31
00:05:19.820 --> 00:05:21.487
{\an8}<i>as we show you
Father Richard Moore...</i>

32
00:05:21.488 --> 00:05:22.989
{\an8}MAN:
What about the parents?

33
00:05:22.990 --> 00:05:24.615
{\an8}MAN 2: They're not
talkin' to the police.

34
00:05:24.616 --> 00:05:25.950
{\an8}Do we charge 'em?

35
00:05:25.951 --> 00:05:28.494
No, even the priest admits
he ran the show.

36
00:05:28.495 --> 00:05:29.829
We need a Christian on this.

37
00:05:29.830 --> 00:05:31.372
{\an8}Preferably a Catholic.

38
00:05:31.373 --> 00:05:33.416
{\an8}Somebody that knows this shit
inside out,

39
00:05:33.417 --> 00:05:35.460
{\an8}and who the public
will see as unbiased.

40
00:05:37.755 --> 00:05:39.965
We're going after
a holy man, here.

41
00:05:41.050 --> 00:05:43.342
Ethan Thomas.

42
00:05:43.343 --> 00:05:47.346
He's not Catholic, though.
Methodist, I think.

43
00:05:47.347 --> 00:05:49.140
{\an8}But the guy practically
lives at church.

44
00:05:49.141 --> 00:05:51.017
{\an8}Choir practice,
teaches Sunday school.

45
00:05:51.018 --> 00:05:52.810
{\an8}Yeah, he's no choirboy
in the courtroom.

46
00:05:52.811 --> 00:05:54.395
I've seen him tear people
up on cross.

47
00:05:54.396 --> 00:05:56.815
He's a shrewd son of a bitch.

48
00:06:00.611 --> 00:06:02.904
{\an8}All right, pull him off
whatever he's doing.

49
00:06:02.905 --> 00:06:04.363
{\an8}He's lead prosecutor.

50
00:06:04.364 --> 00:06:07.034
{\an8}[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

51
00:06:24.927 --> 00:06:27.678
KARL: Now, there's ambition.
She never stops.

52
00:06:27.679 --> 00:06:29.139
She even works while she drinks.

53
00:06:29.140 --> 00:06:30.389
Gentlemen, you know Erin Bruner.

54
00:06:30.390 --> 00:06:31.766
Of course.
Hello.

55
00:06:31.767 --> 00:06:33.768
I was so sure
that Van Hopper would fry,

56
00:06:33.769 --> 00:06:36.687
but you proved me wrong, lady.

57
00:06:36.688 --> 00:06:38.064
The system worked, that's all.

58
00:06:38.065 --> 00:06:39.440
[ALL CHUCKLE]

59
00:06:39.441 --> 00:06:42.485
Gentlemen, you'll excuse us,
will you?

60
00:06:42.486 --> 00:06:44.445
Have you seen the news
about this priest?

61
00:06:44.446 --> 00:06:46.823
I heard something about
an exorcism gone bad,

62
00:06:46.824 --> 00:06:48.241
but I don't know the details.

63
00:06:48.242 --> 00:06:50.160
The DA charged him
with negligent homicide.

64
00:06:50.161 --> 00:06:52.203
They offered
a very reasonable plea bargain.

65
00:06:52.204 --> 00:06:53.496
The priest turned it down.

66
00:06:53.497 --> 00:06:55.748
Karl, do not ask me
to take this...

67
00:06:55.749 --> 00:06:59.418
The archdiocese
specifically requested you.

68
00:06:59.419 --> 00:07:00.753
Why me?

69
00:07:00.754 --> 00:07:02.505
Because they followed
the Van Hopper trial

70
00:07:02.506 --> 00:07:03.547
like everybody else.

71
00:07:03.548 --> 00:07:04.966
They think you're smart.

72
00:07:04.967 --> 00:07:06.592
And convincing.

73
00:07:06.593 --> 00:07:09.095
They want you to ask the priest
to reconsider a deal.

74
00:07:09.096 --> 00:07:10.471
What if he won't?

75
00:07:10.472 --> 00:07:11.848
This case sounds
like a quagmire.

76
00:07:11.849 --> 00:07:13.599
If I'm smart,
I'll leave it alone.

77
00:07:13.600 --> 00:07:18.229
Erin, the Van Hopper case
got you back on the fast track.

78
00:07:18.230 --> 00:07:20.398
Once again,
you're a rising star.

79
00:07:20.399 --> 00:07:21.774
Chivas, neat, please.

80
00:07:21.775 --> 00:07:24.277
Tanqueray martini, dry.

81
00:07:24.278 --> 00:07:25.820
What are you saying?

82
00:07:25.821 --> 00:07:27.446
I'm saying, you do this for me,

83
00:07:27.447 --> 00:07:30.908
and the rising star
keeps rising.

84
00:07:30.909 --> 00:07:32.161
The case is yours.

85
00:07:35.122 --> 00:07:37.875
And just how high do I get
to rise this time?

86
00:07:39.918 --> 00:07:42.420
I've been junior partner
for too long now, Karl.

87
00:07:42.421 --> 00:07:44.797
It's not like other firms
haven't been calling. Erin...

88
00:07:44.798 --> 00:07:48.886
I want my name on the door,
right next to yours.

89
00:07:51.722 --> 00:07:53.181
Okay.

90
00:07:53.182 --> 00:07:54.724
Try to get the deal.

91
00:07:54.725 --> 00:07:56.809
If the priest won't do it
and this does go to trial,

92
00:07:56.810 --> 00:07:58.353
the archdiocese feels
his testimony

93
00:07:58.354 --> 00:07:59.770
could be an embarrassment.

94
00:07:59.771 --> 00:08:01.772
So under no circumstances
is he to testify...

95
00:08:01.773 --> 00:08:03.066
No, of course.

96
00:08:03.067 --> 00:08:04.650
If I'd put
James Van Hopper on the stand,

97
00:08:04.651 --> 00:08:06.236
he'd be marking time
on death row

98
00:08:06.237 --> 00:08:09.072
instead of sunbathing
on Miami Beach.

99
00:08:09.073 --> 00:08:10.366
His tab.

100
00:08:14.745 --> 00:08:16.120
[CELL DOOR SLAMS]

101
00:08:16.121 --> 00:08:18.790
[MEN SHOUTING IN DISTANCE]

102
00:08:35.515 --> 00:08:37.976
Good morning, I'm Erin Bruner.

103
00:08:38.769 --> 00:08:40.562
May I sit down?

104
00:08:42.189 --> 00:08:46.692
They brought the chair
for my public defender.

105
00:08:46.693 --> 00:08:48.236
I guess they left it here

106
00:08:48.237 --> 00:08:51.656
when they decided I wasn't
going to kill myself with it.

107
00:09:00.040 --> 00:09:03.043
My firm represents
the archdiocese.

108
00:09:04.295 --> 00:09:06.421
Yes.

109
00:09:06.422 --> 00:09:08.424
Yes, I was expecting them
to send someone.

110
00:09:10.968 --> 00:09:12.009
Why did they choose you?

111
00:09:12.010 --> 00:09:13.594
I wanted this case.

112
00:09:13.595 --> 00:09:14.846
So you like the spotlight?

113
00:09:15.931 --> 00:09:17.390
I'm used to it.

114
00:09:17.391 --> 00:09:18.891
I defended James Van Hopper.

115
00:09:18.892 --> 00:09:21.145
Now you've come here
to further your celebrity.

116
00:09:21.645 --> 00:09:24.105
No.

117
00:09:24.106 --> 00:09:26.442
I'm here to make
senior partner at my firm.

118
00:09:29.569 --> 00:09:30.569
Are you a Catholic?

119
00:09:30.570 --> 00:09:32.322
No.

120
00:09:32.323 --> 00:09:34.240
I'm... an agnostic, I guess.

121
00:09:34.241 --> 00:09:35.574
I'm not really sure.

122
00:09:35.575 --> 00:09:39.078
If you're not sure,
then you are one.

123
00:09:39.079 --> 00:09:41.580
Sorry, but I don't think you're
the right attorney for me.

124
00:09:41.581 --> 00:09:43.291
I'll stick
with my public defender.

125
00:09:43.292 --> 00:09:46.002
He can't get the DA
to get you a better deal, I can.

126
00:09:46.003 --> 00:09:47.962
I won't be making
any plea agreement.

127
00:09:47.963 --> 00:09:50.256
If you don't, the archdiocese
won't post your bail.

128
00:09:50.257 --> 00:09:52.801
You'll be stuck in here
for the duration of the trial.

129
00:09:55.262 --> 00:09:56.762
Father, do you
understand how long

130
00:09:56.763 --> 00:09:57.930
they can put you away for this?

131
00:09:57.931 --> 00:09:59.307
It's been explained to me.

132
00:09:59.308 --> 00:10:01.392
The district attorney's
office doesn't like it

133
00:10:01.393 --> 00:10:03.311
when religion holds itself
above the law.

134
00:10:03.312 --> 00:10:04.979
And this prosecutor,
Ethan Thomas?

135
00:10:04.980 --> 00:10:08.316
You're gonna need somebody
hungry and smart and aggressive

136
00:10:08.317 --> 00:10:09.650
to even have a chance.

137
00:10:09.651 --> 00:10:11.819
And what would your strategy
be to defend me

138
00:10:11.820 --> 00:10:13.446
against such a formidable man?

139
00:10:13.447 --> 00:10:15.239
That depends.

140
00:10:15.240 --> 00:10:16.366
On what?

141
00:10:16.367 --> 00:10:17.659
On how you wanna be defended.

142
00:10:22.289 --> 00:10:24.123
What's your main concern?

143
00:10:24.124 --> 00:10:25.749
Other than staying out of jail?

144
00:10:25.750 --> 00:10:27.710
Is it how you're being
portrayed in the media?

145
00:10:27.711 --> 00:10:29.504
I don't care
about my reputation.

146
00:10:29.505 --> 00:10:31.590
I'm not afraid of jail.

147
00:10:34.051 --> 00:10:38.429
What I care about
is telling Emily Rose's story.

148
00:10:38.430 --> 00:10:41.015
I want people to hear
what only I can tell.

149
00:10:41.016 --> 00:10:42.266
And what is that?

150
00:10:42.267 --> 00:10:46.771
What really happened
to Emily, and why.

151
00:10:50.234 --> 00:10:52.360
If I let you defend me,

152
00:10:52.361 --> 00:10:54.445
will you promise
to let me testify

153
00:10:54.446 --> 00:10:56.531
and tell the truth about
what happened to Emily?

154
00:10:56.532 --> 00:11:00.659
And what is the truth
you would tell?

155
00:11:00.660 --> 00:11:01.911
That the ritual killed her?

156
00:11:01.912 --> 00:11:03.454
Was it your fault she died?

157
00:11:03.455 --> 00:11:04.455
No.

158
00:11:04.456 --> 00:11:05.706
All right.

159
00:11:05.707 --> 00:11:07.166
Then I'll let you
tell her story.

160
00:11:07.167 --> 00:11:08.501
But only if you agree

161
00:11:08.502 --> 00:11:10.795
to let me do whatever else
it takes to win.

162
00:11:17.177 --> 00:11:18.969
Mm.

163
00:11:18.970 --> 00:11:21.556
[WIND WHISTLING]

164
00:11:21.557 --> 00:11:23.308
[HISSES]

165
00:11:29.731 --> 00:11:33.443
You're not used to
this kind of place.

166
00:11:33.444 --> 00:11:37.155
I'm sure our life
is very strange to you.

167
00:11:38.740 --> 00:11:42.076
Not so strange.

168
00:11:42.077 --> 00:11:44.412
I grew up in a little town.

169
00:11:44.413 --> 00:11:47.373
But our house wasn't as nice
or as big as this.

170
00:11:47.374 --> 00:11:49.208
My mother, sh...
She raised me alone.

171
00:11:49.209 --> 00:11:52.753
She was a schoolteacher,
so we had very little money.

172
00:11:52.754 --> 00:11:56.090
What a wonderful thing to be.

173
00:11:56.091 --> 00:11:58.884
That was Emily's dream:
to be a teacher.

174
00:11:58.885 --> 00:12:03.473
That's why she went away
to the university.

175
00:12:03.474 --> 00:12:05.725
[CATS MEOWING]

176
00:12:09.980 --> 00:12:11.147
A lot of cats live here.

177
00:12:11.148 --> 00:12:12.148
[CHUCKLES]

178
00:12:12.149 --> 00:12:13.650
[LAUGHS]
Oh.

179
00:12:13.651 --> 00:12:15.818
There are, um...

180
00:12:15.819 --> 00:12:18.862
11 now, I think.

181
00:12:18.863 --> 00:12:20.698
Emily always brought them home.

182
00:12:20.699 --> 00:12:22.366
Ever since she was
a little girl,

183
00:12:22.367 --> 00:12:25.454
she... couldn't leave
a stray abandoned.

184
00:12:29.082 --> 00:12:32.960
Before these troubles began,
was Emily a happy girl?

185
00:12:32.961 --> 00:12:35.963
Oh, yes.

186
00:12:35.964 --> 00:12:38.591
Before she went away
to university,

187
00:12:38.592 --> 00:12:41.302
my Emily was so very happy.

188
00:12:41.303 --> 00:12:43.471
<i>[GIRLS LAUGHING]</i>

189
00:12:43.472 --> 00:12:44.681
What is going on?

190
00:12:44.682 --> 00:12:46.391
Girls.

191
00:12:49.645 --> 00:12:51.062
Mama.

192
00:12:53.231 --> 00:12:54.316
Is it...?

193
00:12:56.026 --> 00:12:57.902
It's a scholarship, Mama.

194
00:12:59.154 --> 00:13:01.989
They pay for it.
They pay for everything.

195
00:13:01.990 --> 00:13:04.576
This is your dream, Emily.

196
00:13:06.578 --> 00:13:08.288
You'll be leaving us.

197
00:13:09.414 --> 00:13:11.416
It's okay.

198
00:13:13.418 --> 00:13:15.252
I'll be okay.

199
00:13:15.253 --> 00:13:18.590
I'm gonna show this
to your father.

200
00:13:21.968 --> 00:13:24.095
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

201
00:13:26.181 --> 00:13:27.223
Counselor.

202
00:13:27.224 --> 00:13:29.058
Thanks for meeting me.

203
00:13:29.059 --> 00:13:30.101
Sure.

204
00:13:31.311 --> 00:13:33.270
Can I buy you a drink,
Mr. Thomas?

205
00:13:33.271 --> 00:13:34.772
He makes an excellent martini.

206
00:13:34.773 --> 00:13:37.066
Just water for me, please.

207
00:13:37.067 --> 00:13:38.442
So...

208
00:13:38.443 --> 00:13:40.403
The judge thinks we should
offer your client

209
00:13:40.404 --> 00:13:41.529
a new plea agreement.

210
00:13:41.530 --> 00:13:43.947
Apparently she feels
the community

211
00:13:43.948 --> 00:13:46.200
might be better served
without this trial.

212
00:13:46.201 --> 00:13:47.744
How do you feel about it?

213
00:13:47.745 --> 00:13:49.328
Personally.

214
00:13:49.329 --> 00:13:52.707
My job is to represent
the interests of the people

215
00:13:52.708 --> 00:13:55.000
and make an effort
to be objective.

216
00:13:55.001 --> 00:13:56.669
Mm.

217
00:13:56.670 --> 00:13:59.463
I ask because I know
you're a churchgoer.

218
00:13:59.464 --> 00:14:01.298
Now, you're set to prosecute
a man of God.

219
00:14:01.299 --> 00:14:03.760
Your priest broke the law,

220
00:14:03.761 --> 00:14:06.554
and a young girl is dead.

221
00:14:06.555 --> 00:14:08.180
If he's a man of God,

222
00:14:08.181 --> 00:14:10.683
then, personally, I think he's
even more subject to the laws

223
00:14:10.684 --> 00:14:12.184
of moral behavior
and punishment.

224
00:14:12.185 --> 00:14:13.852
If it were up to me,
he'd get no deal at all.

225
00:14:13.853 --> 00:14:15.979
What about forgiveness
and compassion?

226
00:14:15.980 --> 00:14:18.065
Isn't that part of your creed?

227
00:14:18.066 --> 00:14:20.110
Or does that just
get in the way of your work?

228
00:14:22.904 --> 00:14:25.615
If you have compassion
for your client, counselor,

229
00:14:25.616 --> 00:14:28.075
you'll persuade him
to accept this:

230
00:14:28.076 --> 00:14:30.787
Charges reduced
to reckless endangerment.

231
00:14:30.788 --> 00:14:32.830
Twelve months in a county jail.

232
00:14:32.831 --> 00:14:35.541
Reducible to six plus probation,
if he can stay out of trouble.

233
00:14:35.542 --> 00:14:37.460
Somehow, I expect
he can manage that.

234
00:14:37.461 --> 00:14:38.919
But please understand me.

235
00:14:38.920 --> 00:14:41.547
If he refuses,
I will seek the maximum.

236
00:14:41.548 --> 00:14:44.341
Father Moore has made it clear
there will be no plea agreement.

237
00:14:44.342 --> 00:14:45.843
He will not lie.

238
00:14:45.844 --> 00:14:47.928
He will not admit to something
he is not guilty of.

239
00:14:47.929 --> 00:14:49.639
And he was never
neglectful of Emily.

240
00:14:49.640 --> 00:14:51.557
Never neglectful?

241
00:14:51.558 --> 00:14:53.350
Have you seen
the postmortem photographs?

242
00:14:53.351 --> 00:14:55.813
[♪♪♪]

243
00:14:57.981 --> 00:14:59.649
We'll go to trial.

244
00:14:59.650 --> 00:15:01.693
My client wants the public
to know the truth.

245
00:15:02.527 --> 00:15:04.028
Good.

246
00:15:05.155 --> 00:15:07.115
So do I.

247
00:15:08.533 --> 00:15:10.952
Have a good night, counselor.

248
00:16:08.844 --> 00:16:11.847
[TICKING]

249
00:16:15.225 --> 00:16:16.976
[TICKING STOPS]

250
00:16:19.938 --> 00:16:23.232
JUDGE: <i>Let the record show
that the defendant and his counsel</i>

251
00:16:23.233 --> 00:16:25.693
are present,
and that the jury is seated.

252
00:16:25.694 --> 00:16:28.821
Mr. Thomas, you may begin.

253
00:16:28.822 --> 00:16:30.072
Thank you, Your Honor.

254
00:16:30.073 --> 00:16:31.866
Good morning,
ladies and gentlemen.

255
00:16:31.867 --> 00:16:33.325
My name is Ethan Thomas,

256
00:16:33.326 --> 00:16:35.494
I'm the assistant
district attorney,

257
00:16:35.495 --> 00:16:37.037
and I represent the people.

258
00:16:37.038 --> 00:16:39.456
In the case before you,
the evidence will show

259
00:16:39.457 --> 00:16:42.793
that the victim had
a serious medical condition

260
00:16:42.794 --> 00:16:44.294
that demanded medical treatment.

261
00:16:44.295 --> 00:16:46.756
We will prove
that the victim's condition

262
00:16:46.757 --> 00:16:48.925
rendered her physically

263
00:16:48.926 --> 00:16:54.054
and psychologically incapable
of caring for herself.

264
00:16:54.055 --> 00:16:57.474
Her care... was then
wholly entrusted

265
00:16:57.475 --> 00:17:01.729
to that man, the defendant,
Father Richard Moore.

266
00:17:01.730 --> 00:17:05.608
She became his responsibility.

267
00:17:05.609 --> 00:17:08.485
And he betrayed
that responsibility,

268
00:17:08.486 --> 00:17:11.280
by persuading her to abandon
her medical treatment

269
00:17:11.281 --> 00:17:13.991
in favor of religious treatment.

270
00:17:13.992 --> 00:17:18.245
A ritual exorcism,
performed by the defendant,

271
00:17:18.246 --> 00:17:23.333
allegedly to cure the victim by
ridding her of demonic forces.

272
00:17:23.334 --> 00:17:27.671
We will demonstrate
that this course of action

273
00:17:27.672 --> 00:17:30.800
directly resulted
in the victim's death.

274
00:17:30.801 --> 00:17:34.011
I said a moment ago
that I represent the people.

275
00:17:34.012 --> 00:17:35.512
We all know what that means,

276
00:17:35.513 --> 00:17:37.180
but it's a little abstract,
isn't it?

277
00:17:37.181 --> 00:17:39.976
Miss Bruner,
the attorney for the defense,

278
00:17:39.977 --> 00:17:43.186
is seated right next to
the man she represents.

279
00:17:43.187 --> 00:17:47.065
And I stand here
to represent the people.

280
00:17:47.066 --> 00:17:49.860
That's not really
why I stand here today.

281
00:17:49.861 --> 00:17:55.950
I'm here on behalf of someone
who can't sit at a table...

282
00:17:55.951 --> 00:17:59.036
and look at you every day,
and gain your sympathy.

283
00:17:59.037 --> 00:18:02.539
Someone who can't
take the stand to testify

284
00:18:02.540 --> 00:18:05.794
and tell you what
happened in her own words.

285
00:18:08.338 --> 00:18:09.797
A young girl,

286
00:18:09.798 --> 00:18:11.966
that could have
been your daughter,

287
00:18:11.967 --> 00:18:14.384
could have been mine.

288
00:18:14.385 --> 00:18:16.971
A girl who trusted
Father Richard Moore

289
00:18:16.972 --> 00:18:18.640
with her life.

290
00:18:25.563 --> 00:18:27.231
This is what she looked like...

291
00:18:30.068 --> 00:18:34.364
before the defendant
began his religious treatment.

292
00:18:36.825 --> 00:18:39.994
This is a photograph taken
of her on the day that she died.

293
00:18:39.995 --> 00:18:41.162
[JURORS GASP SOFTLY]

294
00:18:53.675 --> 00:18:58.178
I stand here for Emily Rose,

295
00:18:58.179 --> 00:19:00.557
who died horribly...

296
00:19:02.183 --> 00:19:03.852
...at age 19.

297
00:19:06.521 --> 00:19:08.355
You won't be able
to see Emily sitting here,

298
00:19:08.356 --> 00:19:10.148
day after day,
during this trial.

299
00:19:10.149 --> 00:19:13.528
But I hope you'll remember her
as she was when she was alive...

300
00:19:14.278 --> 00:19:16.907
and full of...

301
00:19:18.199 --> 00:19:20.284
hopes and dreams.

302
00:19:22.954 --> 00:19:25.581
And as she was
when Father Richard Moore

303
00:19:25.582 --> 00:19:27.416
was finished with her,

304
00:19:27.417 --> 00:19:29.753
and left her to die.

305
00:19:33.006 --> 00:19:35.007
Thank you.

306
00:19:35.008 --> 00:19:38.970
Is the defense prepared to
make its opening statement?

307
00:19:41.681 --> 00:19:43.974
Your Honor, I would like
to reserve my opening statement

308
00:19:43.975 --> 00:19:46.226
until the presentation
of the defense's case.

309
00:19:46.227 --> 00:19:47.311
As is your privilege.

310
00:19:48.730 --> 00:19:50.522
JUDGE:
Prosecution may begin.

311
00:19:50.523 --> 00:19:52.816
[WHISPERS] Don't worry,
that was already my plan.

312
00:19:52.817 --> 00:19:55.611
THOMAS: Thank you, Your Honor.
The people call Dr. Edith Vogel.

313
00:19:55.612 --> 00:19:57.821
I've known Emily
her entire life.

314
00:19:57.822 --> 00:20:00.783
I took care of all
of the Rose girls.

315
00:20:00.784 --> 00:20:03.953
THOMAS: Can you describe
Emily as you knew her growing up?

316
00:20:03.954 --> 00:20:06.622
She was a bit sickly
in her early years.

317
00:20:06.623 --> 00:20:11.085
She stayed inside a lot,
reading, learning music.

318
00:20:11.086 --> 00:20:13.003
How did she feel
about going away to school?

319
00:20:13.004 --> 00:20:15.297
Objection, speculation.
Witness is not a psychiatrist.

320
00:20:15.298 --> 00:20:16.757
I'll rephrase.

321
00:20:16.758 --> 00:20:18.842
Did you talk to Emily
about going off to college?

322
00:20:18.843 --> 00:20:21.678
Yes, she told me
she was excited,

323
00:20:21.679 --> 00:20:23.555
but nervous that she would be

324
00:20:23.556 --> 00:20:26.475
away from her family
in the big city.

325
00:20:26.476 --> 00:20:28.602
This was
an overwhelming change for her.

326
00:20:28.603 --> 00:20:30.437
Did you stay in touch
after she went away?

327
00:20:30.438 --> 00:20:32.689
Yes, she wrote me a letter,

328
00:20:32.690 --> 00:20:35.442
saying that she'd been
to a dance

329
00:20:35.443 --> 00:20:38.195
and she'd met a boy named Jason.

330
00:20:38.196 --> 00:20:40.447
She didn't want her mother
to know this,

331
00:20:40.448 --> 00:20:43.033
because her mother
did not approve of dancing

332
00:20:43.034 --> 00:20:45.035
and had warned her
about the boys at school.

333
00:20:45.036 --> 00:20:48.038
And did Emily communicate
with you again last fall

334
00:20:48.039 --> 00:20:49.873
after you received the letter?

335
00:20:49.874 --> 00:20:51.292
Actually, it was her mother.

336
00:20:53.128 --> 00:20:55.378
She telephoned me,

337
00:20:55.379 --> 00:20:58.132
waking me out of a deep sleep
at 4 in the morning.

338
00:20:58.133 --> 00:20:59.341
[THUNDER RUMBLES]

339
00:20:59.342 --> 00:21:01.135
EDITH:
<i>She asked me to call Emily</i>

340
00:21:01.136 --> 00:21:04.138
<i>at a payphone
on the university campus.</i>

341
00:21:04.139 --> 00:21:05.722
[PHONE RINGS]

342
00:21:05.723 --> 00:21:09.392
<i>When Emily answered,
she was quite hysterical.</i>

343
00:21:09.393 --> 00:21:11.145
[SOBBING]

344
00:21:11.146 --> 00:21:14.982
<i>At first she just sobbed
uncontrollably.</i>

345
00:21:14.983 --> 00:21:16.900
<i>Eventually
she calmed down enough</i>

346
00:21:16.901 --> 00:21:18.903
<i>to tell me what had happened.</i>

347
00:21:20.613 --> 00:21:23.740
<i>She said that she was alone
that weekend.</i>

348
00:21:23.741 --> 00:21:26.243
<i>Her roommate had gone home.</i>

349
00:21:26.244 --> 00:21:29.080
[THUNDER RUMBLES]

350
00:21:29.831 --> 00:21:32.708
<i>She had awakened...</i>

351
00:21:32.709 --> 00:21:35.879
<i>and thought she smelled
something burning.</i>

352
00:21:37.214 --> 00:21:40.340
<i>There was no alarm,
but she got up,</i>

353
00:21:40.341 --> 00:21:42.760
<i>afraid there was a fire.</i>

354
00:21:45.096 --> 00:21:48.266
[♪♪♪]

355
00:21:54.856 --> 00:21:56.440
[THUNDER RUMBLES]

356
00:22:23.467 --> 00:22:26.304
[CRASH]

357
00:22:32.643 --> 00:22:34.979
[WIND HOWLING]

358
00:23:01.422 --> 00:23:04.175
[THUNDER RUMBLES]

359
00:23:20.441 --> 00:23:22.485
[RATTLE]

360
00:23:25.947 --> 00:23:29.326
[♪♪♪]

361
00:23:43.089 --> 00:23:45.132
[WOOD CREAKING]

362
00:23:45.133 --> 00:23:47.218
[GASPING]

363
00:23:55.810 --> 00:23:57.812
[WOOD CREAKS]

364
00:24:01.816 --> 00:24:03.693
[GAGGING]

365
00:24:28.843 --> 00:24:30.761
[SCREAMING]

366
00:24:38.353 --> 00:24:40.020
THOMAS:
<i>Dr. Mueller,</i>

367
00:24:40.021 --> 00:24:42.272
<i>what's your position
at the university hospital?</i>

368
00:24:42.273 --> 00:24:45.150
I am chairman
of the Department of Neurology.

369
00:24:45.151 --> 00:24:47.944
And after you heard about
the dorm-room incident,

370
00:24:47.945 --> 00:24:49.654
what were your initial thoughts?

371
00:24:49.655 --> 00:24:52.782
At first, I thought perhaps
Emily had taken illegal drugs,

372
00:24:52.783 --> 00:24:55.327
some type of hallucinogen.

373
00:24:55.328 --> 00:24:58.747
But we ran tests and found
no trace of drugs in her system.

374
00:24:58.748 --> 00:25:01.250
And the more she explained
the incident to me,

375
00:25:01.251 --> 00:25:04.920
the more I began to suspect
something else.

376
00:25:04.921 --> 00:25:07.172
Epilepsy results
from rapid, uncontrolled

377
00:25:07.173 --> 00:25:09.299
electrical activity
in the brain.

378
00:25:09.300 --> 00:25:12.386
<i>In a severe,
or grand mal seizure,</i>

379
00:25:12.387 --> 00:25:14.888
<i>a person may lose consciousness
for several minutes</i>

380
00:25:14.889 --> 00:25:16.223
<i>and suffer
involuntary contractions</i>

381
00:25:16.224 --> 00:25:18.308
<i>of all the muscles of the body.</i>

382
00:25:18.309 --> 00:25:21.019
THOMAS: <i>Is it possible for a
person suffering from such a seizure</i>

383
00:25:21.020 --> 00:25:22.562
<i>to have hallucinations</i>

384
00:25:22.563 --> 00:25:24.773
<i>or perceive the things
that Emily described?</i>

385
00:25:24.774 --> 00:25:26.524
<i>The muscle contractions
could feel</i>

386
00:25:26.525 --> 00:25:28.360
<i>like an extreme pressure
on the body,</i>

387
00:25:28.361 --> 00:25:31.280
<i>and it is certainly possible
with all that brain activity</i>

388
00:25:31.281 --> 00:25:32.989
for a person to perceive

389
00:25:32.990 --> 00:25:35.658
all sorts of strange
and violent things.

390
00:25:35.659 --> 00:25:38.578
So suspecting
that Emily was epileptic,

391
00:25:38.579 --> 00:25:39.829
how did you proceed?

392
00:25:39.830 --> 00:25:41.915
I administered
an electroencephalograph.

393
00:25:41.916 --> 00:25:43.333
What did the EEG reveal?

394
00:25:43.334 --> 00:25:45.794
It showed
a possible epileptic focus

395
00:25:45.795 --> 00:25:47.796
in the patient's
left temporal lobe.

396
00:25:47.797 --> 00:25:49.881
Did this require
specific treatment?

397
00:25:49.882 --> 00:25:51.841
Yes, I began
a medication schedule for Emily

398
00:25:51.842 --> 00:25:53.551
with the drug Gambutrol.

399
00:25:53.552 --> 00:25:57.431
I also advised regular follow-up
examinations and further tests.

400
00:25:57.432 --> 00:26:00.600
But Emily failed to keep her
follow-up appointments with me.

401
00:26:00.601 --> 00:26:02.018
Did she give any reason

402
00:26:02.019 --> 00:26:03.895
for discontinuing
these appointments?

403
00:26:03.896 --> 00:26:06.398
Yes, she told me she was
convinced that her condition

404
00:26:06.399 --> 00:26:07.774
was a spiritual one.

405
00:26:07.775 --> 00:26:10.527
It was the conviction
of her priest, she said,

406
00:26:10.528 --> 00:26:12.070
and she shared his beliefs.

407
00:26:12.071 --> 00:26:14.490
Doctor, was it your impression
Emily placed her care

408
00:26:14.491 --> 00:26:15.907
entirely
in Father Moore's hands?

409
00:26:15.908 --> 00:26:17.867
Objection,
he's leading the witness.

410
00:26:17.868 --> 00:26:19.829
JUDGE:
Sustained.

411
00:26:21.372 --> 00:26:23.957
After the end of October,
did you ask Emily

412
00:26:23.958 --> 00:26:26.960
why she had stopped filling
her Gambutrol prescriptions?

413
00:26:26.961 --> 00:26:28.295
Yes.

414
00:26:28.296 --> 00:26:30.630
She said that Father Moore
had suggested

415
00:26:30.631 --> 00:26:31.798
she stop taking the drug.

416
00:26:31.799 --> 00:26:33.342
And what,
in your medical opinion,

417
00:26:33.343 --> 00:26:35.927
was the direct result
of Father Moore's suggestion?

418
00:26:35.928 --> 00:26:38.388
I firmly believe Father Moore's
suggestion killed her.

419
00:26:38.389 --> 00:26:40.474
Objection, Your Honor.
The witness is asserting

420
00:26:40.475 --> 00:26:43.352
outrageous conclusions
based on pure hearsay evidence.

421
00:26:43.353 --> 00:26:45.103
Technically correct,

422
00:26:45.104 --> 00:26:48.857
but I'll allow it, as part of
his expert opinion testimony.

423
00:26:48.858 --> 00:26:50.567
Thank you, Dr. Mueller.

424
00:26:50.568 --> 00:26:52.319
Your witness.

425
00:26:52.320 --> 00:26:55.989
Doctor, you said you observed
a <i>possible</i> epileptic focus

426
00:26:55.990 --> 00:26:57.782
in the temporal lobe.

427
00:26:57.783 --> 00:26:59.576
Doesn't this imply
that what you observed

428
00:26:59.577 --> 00:27:01.161
may not have been
an epileptic focus?

429
00:27:01.162 --> 00:27:02.996
Yes, that's also possible.

430
00:27:02.997 --> 00:27:05.374
And would Father Moore's advice
to stop taking Gambutrol

431
00:27:05.375 --> 00:27:08.043
be good advice if Emily were,
in fact, not epileptic?

432
00:27:08.044 --> 00:27:09.627
Of course.

433
00:27:09.628 --> 00:27:11.838
But that's not the case here.
She was epileptic.

434
00:27:11.839 --> 00:27:14.424
Really?

435
00:27:14.425 --> 00:27:17.344
When Emily saw objects
move on their own,

436
00:27:17.345 --> 00:27:20.180
and felt an invisible
presence on top of her,

437
00:27:20.181 --> 00:27:22.891
was she experiencing symptoms
typical of epilepsy?

438
00:27:22.892 --> 00:27:24.393
Not typical, no.

439
00:27:24.394 --> 00:27:27.521
Are they typical indications
of any other conditions?

440
00:27:27.522 --> 00:27:28.813
Say, for example, psychosis?

441
00:27:28.814 --> 00:27:30.566
Yes, I would say that's correct.

442
00:27:30.567 --> 00:27:34.069
But isn't psychosis an entirely
different medical condition

443
00:27:34.070 --> 00:27:35.111
from epilepsy?

444
00:27:35.112 --> 00:27:36.738
Yes, in my experience, it is.

445
00:27:36.739 --> 00:27:39.282
So, doctor, aren't you
selectively choosing what parts

446
00:27:39.283 --> 00:27:41.577
of Emily's experiences
fit your epilepsy diagnosis

447
00:27:41.578 --> 00:27:44.120
while simply ignoring those
which might indicate otherwise?

448
00:27:44.121 --> 00:27:46.122
Objection, Your Honor,
argumentative.

449
00:27:46.123 --> 00:27:47.916
Withdrawn.

450
00:27:47.917 --> 00:27:49.586
No further questions.

451
00:27:56.593 --> 00:27:59.136
[MAN YELLING IN DISTANCE]

452
00:28:01.680 --> 00:28:03.765
[VOICE WHISPERING IN LATIN]

453
00:28:03.766 --> 00:28:08.229
[♪♪♪]

454
00:28:18.406 --> 00:28:20.283
[LATCH CLICKS]

455
00:28:22.452 --> 00:28:24.327
We have to work fast.

456
00:28:24.328 --> 00:28:26.955
They're only giving me
an hour with you tonight.

457
00:28:26.956 --> 00:28:27.915
Listen, um...

458
00:28:27.916 --> 00:28:29.791
Listen.

459
00:28:29.792 --> 00:28:32.919
Before we get started, there's
something I have to tell you.

460
00:28:32.920 --> 00:28:34.588
Something I should have
said to you

461
00:28:34.589 --> 00:28:36.172
before I let you take the case.

462
00:28:36.173 --> 00:28:37.258
Okay.

463
00:28:40.219 --> 00:28:44.139
There are... forces
surrounding this trial.

464
00:28:44.140 --> 00:28:48.018
Dark... powerful forces.

465
00:28:49.019 --> 00:28:51.563
Just be careful, Erin.

466
00:28:51.564 --> 00:28:52.690
Watch your step.

467
00:28:54.358 --> 00:28:55.859
I see.

468
00:28:57.778 --> 00:29:00.029
Look...

469
00:29:00.030 --> 00:29:02.824
Father, you don't have
to worry about me.

470
00:29:02.825 --> 00:29:04.409
I'm an agnostic, remember?

471
00:29:04.410 --> 00:29:07.162
Look, demons exist whether
you believe in them or not.

472
00:29:07.163 --> 00:29:09.498
And your involvement
in this trial

473
00:29:09.499 --> 00:29:11.667
might just open you up
to their attacks.

474
00:29:11.668 --> 00:29:16.087
Look, Father, I appreciate
your concern, but...

475
00:29:16.088 --> 00:29:18.173
you need to be worried
about yourself.

476
00:29:18.174 --> 00:29:19.675
Ethan Thomas is using

477
00:29:19.676 --> 00:29:21.968
the medical aspects
of this case as ammunition,

478
00:29:21.969 --> 00:29:25.263
and I have to be prepared
for his attacks, so...

479
00:29:25.264 --> 00:29:27.807
with what little time we have,

480
00:29:27.808 --> 00:29:31.812
I think we need to focus
on your defense.

481
00:29:34.398 --> 00:29:36.192
Oh.

482
00:29:43.449 --> 00:29:45.367
Now, what I need
from you is, uh,

483
00:29:45.368 --> 00:29:47.536
more information about
Emily's condition.

484
00:29:47.537 --> 00:29:50.330
The specific details
of how it progressed

485
00:29:50.331 --> 00:29:51.956
after the dorm-room episode.

486
00:29:51.957 --> 00:29:54.209
Well, after the first incident,

487
00:29:54.210 --> 00:29:56.294
she was sent
to the university hospital

488
00:29:56.295 --> 00:30:00.006
<i>for testing
and, uh, observation.</i>

489
00:30:00.007 --> 00:30:02.426
[♪♪♪]

490
00:30:07.181 --> 00:30:08.390
[THUNDER CRASHES]

491
00:30:08.391 --> 00:30:09.684
[GASPS]

