00:40:54.286 --> 00:40:56.329
JUDGE: Counsel
Bruner, my courtroom day

574
00:40:56.330 --> 00:40:58.497
begins at 9:30 a.m.

575
00:40:58.498 --> 00:40:59.707
I'm sorry, Your Honor, I...

576
00:40:59.708 --> 00:41:02.669
Which was 17 minutes ago.

577
00:41:04.171 --> 00:41:06.256
Ready to proceed?

578
00:41:07.257 --> 00:41:08.299
Yes, Your Honor.

579
00:41:08.300 --> 00:41:09.675
THOMAS:
<i>Dr. Briggs,</i>

580
00:41:09.676 --> 00:41:11.635
please state your qualifications
for the court.

581
00:41:11.636 --> 00:41:15.390
BRIGGS: I have advanced
degrees in medicine, psychiatry,

582
00:41:15.391 --> 00:41:16.932
neurology from Johns Hopkins,

583
00:41:16.933 --> 00:41:21.062
And I have had three books
and several dozen papers

584
00:41:21.063 --> 00:41:23.356
published in the fields
of neurology

585
00:41:23.357 --> 00:41:24.982
and neuropsychiatry.

586
00:41:24.983 --> 00:41:27.526
What was the cause of death,
as determined by the autopsy?

587
00:41:27.527 --> 00:41:30.654
The decedent expired
due to a gradual shutdown

588
00:41:30.655 --> 00:41:31.822
of the bodily functions.

589
00:41:31.823 --> 00:41:34.116
Why did her body shut down?

590
00:41:34.117 --> 00:41:37.286
The autopsy found that, uh,
it was a cumulative effect

591
00:41:37.287 --> 00:41:40.998
from numerous physical traumas
exacerbated by malnutrition,

592
00:41:40.999 --> 00:41:43.500
which severely inhibited
her ability

593
00:41:43.501 --> 00:41:45.878
to recuperate
from those traumas.

594
00:41:45.879 --> 00:41:47.463
Um, in other words,

595
00:41:47.464 --> 00:41:50.799
her starving body had
little or no means to recover

596
00:41:50.800 --> 00:41:52.468
from the injuries
it was sustaining,

597
00:41:52.469 --> 00:41:54.345
and so it eventually
just gave out.

598
00:41:54.346 --> 00:41:56.013
How did Emily
get these injuries?

599
00:41:56.014 --> 00:41:59.850
Some were the result of
violent epileptic seizures,

600
00:41:59.851 --> 00:42:02.270
and some were self-inflicted.

601
00:42:02.271 --> 00:42:04.605
And why, in your opinion,
did Emily injure herself?

602
00:42:04.606 --> 00:42:06.232
And why did she stop eating?

603
00:42:06.233 --> 00:42:09.610
Upon review of
her complete medical file,

604
00:42:09.611 --> 00:42:12.238
I concluded
that Emily's epilepsy

605
00:42:12.239 --> 00:42:14.115
had evolved into
a condition known as

606
00:42:14.116 --> 00:42:15.866
psychotic epileptic disorder.

607
00:42:15.867 --> 00:42:18.035
This is a rare development,
to be sure.

608
00:42:18.036 --> 00:42:20.496
But one that I have witnessed
numerous times.

609
00:42:20.497 --> 00:42:23.124
You mean that Emily was
both epileptic and psychotic?

610
00:42:23.125 --> 00:42:24.125
Yes.

611
00:42:24.126 --> 00:42:25.542
Please explain how this

612
00:42:25.543 --> 00:42:27.753
psychotic epileptic disorder
would manifest itself.

613
00:42:27.754 --> 00:42:29.255
The seizures would have

614
00:42:29.256 --> 00:42:31.006
<i>the characteristic symptoms
of schizophrenia</i>

615
00:42:31.007 --> 00:42:34.760
<i>such as auditory
and visual hallucinations</i>

616
00:42:34.761 --> 00:42:36.720
<i>and sometimes extreme paranoia.</i>

617
00:42:36.721 --> 00:42:38.473
<i>The seizures may lock up</i>

618
00:42:38.474 --> 00:42:40.891
<i>the joints
and slightly contort the body.</i>

619
00:42:40.892 --> 00:42:42.893
<i>The pupils will dilate,</i>

620
00:42:42.894 --> 00:42:44.853
<i>making the eyes appear black.</i>

621
00:42:44.854 --> 00:42:46.397
So you believe she had epilepsy,

622
00:42:46.398 --> 00:42:48.274
which developed
into a violent psychosis,

623
00:42:48.275 --> 00:42:49.733
a condition
that can be controlled

624
00:42:49.734 --> 00:42:51.486
with the drug Gambutrol?

625
00:42:51.487 --> 00:42:54.405
Yes. And it would've been if
she'd continued her treatment.

626
00:42:54.406 --> 00:42:55.697
Dr. Briggs,
in your opinion,

627
00:42:55.698 --> 00:42:57.533
if Emily continued
with her medication,

628
00:42:57.534 --> 00:42:58.659
would she be alive today?

629
00:42:58.660 --> 00:43:00.828
Absolutely.

630
00:43:00.829 --> 00:43:02.788
If treated early,

631
00:43:02.789 --> 00:43:06.625
psychotic epileptic disorder is
rarely fatal.

632
00:43:06.626 --> 00:43:08.336
I mean, this...

633
00:43:08.337 --> 00:43:11.297
This was a very sick girl.

634
00:43:11.298 --> 00:43:13.799
The defendant
should have realized

635
00:43:13.800 --> 00:43:18.095
that Emily was in need
of continued medical treatment.

636
00:43:18.096 --> 00:43:19.305
Thank you, doctor.

637
00:43:19.306 --> 00:43:20.890
Your witness.

638
00:43:23.977 --> 00:43:25.811
Doctor, you testified
that Gambutrol

639
00:43:25.812 --> 00:43:27.771
could have controlled
Emily's condition.

640
00:43:27.772 --> 00:43:28.814
Mm-hmm.

641
00:43:28.815 --> 00:43:30.232
How do you know that?

642
00:43:30.233 --> 00:43:33.569
It's the inevitable result
of taking the drug.

643
00:43:33.570 --> 00:43:36.030
Gambutrol would have controlled
her epileptic seizures,

644
00:43:36.031 --> 00:43:38.533
which were the root cause
of her psychosis.

645
00:43:38.534 --> 00:43:41.035
But wasn't Emily still
experiencing psychotic symptoms

646
00:43:41.036 --> 00:43:43.204
even after she started
taking the medication?

647
00:43:43.205 --> 00:43:44.455
Yes.

648
00:43:44.456 --> 00:43:46.415
Because Gambutrol has
a cumulative effect.

649
00:43:46.416 --> 00:43:49.001
It... It takes time to build up
in the patient's system.

650
00:43:49.002 --> 00:43:51.462
So you assume that Gambutrol
would've helped her,

651
00:43:51.463 --> 00:43:52.588
but you don't know that.

652
00:43:52.589 --> 00:43:55.007
It's a reasonable assumption,
but...

653
00:43:55.008 --> 00:43:57.009
No, of course,
I can't be certain.

654
00:43:57.010 --> 00:43:58.802
Hm.

655
00:43:58.803 --> 00:44:04.266
Doctor, is psychotic epileptic
disorder a common medical term,

656
00:44:04.267 --> 00:44:05.851
or did you just make it up?

657
00:44:05.852 --> 00:44:09.146
I distinguished and named
the illness...

658
00:44:09.147 --> 00:44:12.649
So psychotic epileptic disorder
is just your own pet theory.

659
00:44:12.650 --> 00:44:14.693
Objection, argumentative.
Sustained.

660
00:44:14.694 --> 00:44:18.406
When Emily chose to stop
her medical treatment...

661
00:44:18.407 --> 00:44:20.949
what exactly do you think
should have been done?

662
00:44:20.950 --> 00:44:23.077
Upon recognizing her condition,

663
00:44:23.078 --> 00:44:25.746
I would have tranquilized her
and force-fed her.

664
00:44:25.747 --> 00:44:27.706
And then, if necessary,

665
00:44:27.707 --> 00:44:30.042
I would have treated her
with electroconvulsive therapy.

666
00:44:30.043 --> 00:44:31.085
Electroshock therapy.

667
00:44:31.086 --> 00:44:32.378
Hm.

668
00:44:32.379 --> 00:44:34.671
You would have done this
against her will.

669
00:44:34.672 --> 00:44:36.758
To save her life?

670
00:44:39.553 --> 00:44:41.470
Absolutely.

671
00:44:41.471 --> 00:44:43.473
[♪♪♪]

672
00:44:49.938 --> 00:44:50.980
Nothing further.

673
00:44:54.901 --> 00:44:56.819
JUDGE:
The witness may step down.

674
00:44:57.779 --> 00:44:58.987
Your Honor,

675
00:44:58.988 --> 00:45:00.697
I offer into evidence
this photograph

676
00:45:00.698 --> 00:45:02.324
as People's Exhibit 3-A.

677
00:45:02.325 --> 00:45:03.992
In having done so,
the people rest.

678
00:45:03.993 --> 00:45:06.245
JUDGE: The photo is
entered into evidence.

679
00:45:06.246 --> 00:45:11.375
We are recessed until
tomorrow morning, 9:30 sharp,

680
00:45:11.376 --> 00:45:15.129
at which time, the defense
will give its opening statement

681
00:45:15.130 --> 00:45:16.339
and call its first witness.

682
00:45:17.549 --> 00:45:19.383
I'm sorry I was late.

